<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aho, Haavisto Seek `Positive' EU Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aho, Haavisto Seek `Positive' EU Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706163294 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1300 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Prime Minister Esko Aho has appealed to the 
Center Party congress for a positive European Union [EU] 
membership decision. Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto, the 
former chairman of the MTK [Central Union of Agricultural 
Producers] also leaned toward EU membership in his speech. 
[passage omitted] 
  Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto and Prime Minister Esko Aho 
have dispelled the Center Party members' concern about security 
policy. According to Haavisto, Finland must be able to be there 
and influence the intergovernmental congress of the EU in 1996. 
According to Prime Minister Aho, there is justification for a 
national referendum if there are any considerable foreign and 
security policy changes concerning Finland. 
  [Begin Aho recording] NATO membership is not in any way 
directly connected to Finland's membership in the EU. My 
starting point is that if the EU makes decisions that 
fundamentally change the bases according to which accession is 
now taking place, then of course, just like in other countries, 
that must be separately ratified nationally. Surely, if 
fundamental changes are made to the bases of our security 
policy, then we will come to a situation where the use of a 
national referendum is justified. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

