<H3> <TI>   Tells Ankara To Stop `Causing Tension' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tells Ankara To Stop `Causing Tension' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1806202694 Athens ET-1 Television Network in 1800 GMT 18 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1806202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  1800 </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today said 
that Turkey must stop causing artificial tension. At the same 
time Ankara was criticized by European Union [EU] Commissioner 
Hans van den Broek. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent Nikos Meletis] Government 
Spokesman Venizelos today said that the possibility of a 
Greek-Turkish summit meeting has not been raised. The spokesman 
characteristically stressed there will not be another meeting 
like that in Davos, Switzerland. 
  [Venizelos] Theoretically we have never ruled out such a 
possibility, but there are no plans and no specific proposal or 
desire for something like that. What is important is that the 
cycle of artificial tension must stop. 
  [Meletis] Venizelos repeated that the only outstanding 
difference between Greece and Turkey is over the drawing of the 
boundaries on the continental shelf. All other so-called 
differences are unilateral Turkish demands and cannot be part of 
a dialogue. 
  At the same time, in Ankara they are thinking seriously 
following yesterday's criticism by EU Commissioner Van den 
Broek, who made it clear that the deterioration in respect for 
human rights and the lack of progress in the Cyprus issue 
constitute serious obstacles in EU-Turkey relations. These 
statements were made just one day after the Constitutional 
Court's decision to dissolve the pro-Kurdish Democratic Party, a 
decision which has drawn a lot of reaction. [passage omitted] 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

