<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Holds News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1706192494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1706192494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] President Suleyman Demirel has stated that with its 
democratic, secular, and liberal economy, Turkey will be able to 
contribute to regional stability if it becomes a full member of 
the European Union [EU]. Hans van den Broek, EU commissioner 
responsible for foreign relations, has concluded his contacts in 
Ankara. Demirel received van den Broek and the delegation 
accompanying him at Cankaya Mansion. Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin also participated in the meeting. 
  According to a statement issued by the Press Center of the 
President's Office, van den Broek stated that the EU is aware of 
Turkey's importance as a regional power. 
  Demirel said that Turkey should not lag behind East and 
Central European countries in attaining full membership in the 
EU. At the meeting, Demirel stressed that the Cyprus issue 
should be solved between the two communities and should not pose 
an obstacle to Turkish-EU relations. 
  Cetin and van den Broek held a joint news conference after 
the meetings between the Turkish and the EU delegations. Cetin 
said Turkey has integral economic, political, and security 
relations with the EU. Van den Broek, in turn, stated that the 
EU is against terrorism and fully supports Turkey in its efforts 
to defend its territorial integrity through the democratization 
package. On the human rights issue, van den Broek said that the 
struggle he waged in the past has made President Demirel a hero 
of democracy. 

</TEXT>

