<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Sends Letters to Iran, Greece on PKK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demirel Sends Letters to Iran, Greece on PKK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1906151294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1400 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1906151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 19 (A.A.) -- President Suleyman 
Demirel sent a letter to his Iranian counterpart 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani and Greek counterpart Konstandinos Karamanlis 
on prevention of the separatist terrorist PKK [Workers Party of 
Kurdistan] organization's activities in their countries, it was 
reported on Sunday [19 June]. 
  Presidential Press Center, in a written statement, said 
Demirel sent a letter to Rafsanjani on May 31 and expressed 
pleasure on Turkish-Iranian cooperation against terrorism. 
  Demirel said joint struggle on the issue is for the benefit 
of the two countries `we call for Iran to take necessary 
measures against the PKK terrorists who were reported to be 
existing in Iran.' 
  The Press Center said Rafsanjani replied the letter by 
sending a message with Iranian Interior Minister 'Ali Mohammad 
Besharati. 
  The message said Turkish-Iranian cooperation on security is 
contributing to the two country relations adding that Iran is 
determined to take measures against PKK. 
  The statement also said Demirel had sent a letter to 
Karamanlis on June 2 saying that necessary measures should be 
taken against the separatist terrorist organization. 
  Demirel said France and Germany banned the organization's 
activities and the other countries are closely following the 
activities `however' he added `we learned that PKK has opened a 
bureau in Athens under another name and terrorists caught in 
Turkey said they were trained in camps in Greece.' 
  The statement reported Demirel as saying `Turkish-Greek 
relations would be destroyed if these come true.' 
  Karamanlis in reply said Greece did not allow PKK's 
terrorist 
activities on its territory adding that it seriously condemned 
terrorism to continue good neighboring [as received] relations. 
  The Foreign Ministry earlier summoned the Greek ambassador 
and asked for information from Athens on confessions made by a 
number of PKK members. 
  The terrorists, during their interrogation said that they 
received training in Greece. 
  Athens had denied the statements of terrorists. 

</TEXT>

