<H3> <TI>   Dehaene Announces Candidacy for EU Presidency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dehaene Announces Candidacy for EU Presidency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706144194 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1400 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene is now an official 
candidate for the presidency of the European Commission to 
succeed Jacques Delors. The announcement was made a moment ago 
at the end of today's cabinet meeting. (Philippe Valcoviaque), 
can you tell us how the news was announced? 
  [Valcoviaque] It is now official: The government is backing 
Jean-Luc Dehaene to succeed Jacques Delors as president of the 
European Commission. This was announced at the end of today's 
cabinet meeting. The government also said it hoped a consensus 
could be found in support of Dehaene's candidacy at the Corfu 
European summit next week. 
  After weeks of uncertainty, Jean-Luc Dehaene and the Belgian 
Government have broken their silence. Jean-Luc Dehaene himself 
remained cautious. He hoped the decision would be made in 
Corfu. It would be good for Europe, he said, if things did not 
drag on too long. 
  As to his possible successor as Belgian prime minister, 
Jean-Luc Dehaene said there was no reason to worry about the 
problem until the situation came up. 

</TEXT>

