<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Urged To Reject Conditional U.S. Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Urged To Reject Conditional U.S. Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1906195794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1906195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Nationalist Action Party [NAP] leader Alpaslan 
Turkes has said that the condition imposed by the U.S. Senate on 
aid to Turkey is tantamount to interference in our domestic 
affairs. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Ankara, Turkes recalled 
that 
the U.S. Senate put the condition that the aid to be extended to 
Turkey cannot be used in domestic security. Noting that this 
decision was made as a result of the influence of the Greek, 
Serbian, and PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] lobbies in the 
United States, Turkes said that it is humiliating. 
  [Begin Turkes recording] Our advise to our government is to 
categorically reject this aid. The government should announce 
that a conditional aid is unacceptable. [end recording] 
  Turkes noted that the blind eye turned by the Clinton 
administration to this decision is construed by NAP as an 
indirect support for the PKK. He added that if the government's 
decision to reject the conditional aid is well presented to the 
Turkish workers in Europe, the amount of the aid rejected can be 
collected as donations from these workers. He concluded by 
saying that his party will support such a move. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

