<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   WEU Countries Offer `Logistical Support' for Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    WEU Countries Offer `Logistical Support' for Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106105694 Paris AFP in English 1022 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2106105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, June 21 (AFP) -- Some of France's partners 
in the Western European Union (WEU) are prepared to provide 
"logistical support" to a proposed French-led military 
intervention to end ethnic bloodletting in Rwanda, WEU sources 
said Tuesday [21 June]. 
  The sources said Italy had again pledged to supply troops 
for 
the operation. 
  They added both commitments were conditional on the UN 
Security Council endorsing the operation and on the 
participation of African countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43636 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu119aa_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-119 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Asks DPRK for Visas for New Inspectors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Asks DPRK for Visas for New Inspectors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2006160294 Paris AFP in English 1511 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2006160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Vienna, June 20 (AFP) -- The International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has asked North Korea for visas for 
two new inspectors, following Pyongyang's concessions to former 
U.S. President Jimmy Carter, IAEA spokesman Hans Friedrich Meyer 
said Monday [20 June]. 
  He said the delivery of visas would be a test of North 
Korea's will to resolve the latest crisis, sparked by its 
refusal to allow IAEA inspections of a nuclear reactor suspected 
of diverting fuel for military use. [passage omitted] 
  Two inspectors are already in North Korea at the Yongbyon 
experimental reactor, but they must be replaced after having 
worked under difficult conditions, the Agency said. 
  Yongbyon had discharged some 8,000 nuclear waste rods before 
the inspectors could get there to supervise the process, but 
they are still too hot for any extraction of plutonium, Meyer 
said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

