<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Reportedly Supports Dehaene for EC Presidency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi Reportedly Supports Dehaene for EC Presidency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2006145394 Groot Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD in Dutch 20 Jun 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BR2006145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Groot Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GF/PVDD: "Van Miert Supports Dehaene for EC </F>
Presidency -- And Demands Ministerial Position for 
Dutch-speaking Socialist Party"] 
  [Excerpts] European Competition Commissioner Karel Van 
Miert believes that "Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene is one of 
the few people who can deal with the complex position of 
European Commission (EC) president." In an interview with DE 
STANDAARD, Van Miert said: "I will be pleased when he gets it." 
He also thinks that if Dehaene does become EC president, the 
Christian People's Party should relinquish a ministerial 
position in the federal government to the Dutch-speaking 
Socialist Party. In the meantime Dehaene seems to be gaining 
ever more support abroad. [passage omitted] 
  Prime Minister Dehaene's cabinet confirmed that the premier 
had talks with his Italian colleague Silvio Berlusconi in Rome 
on Friday evening [17 June], after talks with the German 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Netherlands Prime Minister Ruud 
Lubbers. Berlusconi will receive British candidate Sir Leon 
Brittan in the near future. 
  From a German source, it was reported that Italy preferred 
Dehaene to his Netherlands counterpart Lubbers. German 
Chancellor Kohl is reported to have informed Dehaene of this 
preference. On the basis of this information, the Belgian prime 
minister is said to have publicly announced his candidacy to 
succeed Jacques Delors and visit his Italian colleague. 
  Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez let it be known via 
his foreign minister that he would not veto Dehaene's 
appointment. 

</TEXT>

