<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Rejects U.S. Plan for Troop Costs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Rejects U.S. Plan for Troop Costs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106090494 Hilversum Radio Netherlands in English 0830 GMT 
21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hilversum Radio Netherlands </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dutch Defense Minister Relus ter Beek has rejected 
draft legislation in the United States which would require 
European members of NATO to pay 75 percent of the costs of 
keeping U.S. forces stationed on their territory. 
  The proposed law was approved by the U.S. House of 
Representatives last month, but still has to be passed by the 
Senate. Under the law, Washington would pull a large part of 
its troops out of Europe if the NATO allies were not to agree to 
pay 75 percent of the costs. 
  In Washington, the Dutch defense minister told U.S. 
Secretary 
of Defense William Perry he found the proposals unacceptable. 
Minister ter Beek said the planned burden-sharing was anything 
but fair. 

</TEXT>

