<H3> <TI>   Martino: Problems With Slovenia `Small Scale' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martino: Problems With Slovenia `Small Scale' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1406090894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1832 GMT 13 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1406090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Slovenia/Italy: Martino on </F>
Relations"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Luxembourg, June 13 -- Italy's Foreign 
Minister Antonio Martino played down reported friction with 
Slovenia, Monday [13 June], saying that the problems which have 
arisen are "rather small scale." 
  Martino pointed out that a joint committee is already at 
work 
on resolving outstanding issues, after which "we will support, 
with sincere enthusiasm, an association deal between Slovenia 
and the European Union [EU]." 
  Martino was speaking on the sidelines of a meeting of EU 
diplomatic chiefs to lay the groundwork for the June 24-25 EU 
summit in Corfu. Slovenia was one of the items on the agenda 
for today's talks. 
  Geography has "condemned Italy and Slovenia to being 
neighbours" and "history has condemned them to being friends" 
said Martino in a press conference, "I am convinced that these 
two countries will remain friends." 
  At the centre of the friction has been Italy's reluctance to 
back a Slovenian EU membership bid until the former Yugoslav 
state has fulfilled all the conditions of the Osimo Treaty which 
fixed borders between Italy and Yugoslavia. Italy is demanding 
that Italians be allowed to regain land in Istria confiscated by 
Yugoslav authorities. 

</TEXT>

