<H3> <TI>   FDP Rejects Bundeswehr `Police Reserve' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FDP Rejects Bundeswehr `Police Reserve' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2006193594 Hamburg DPA in German 1410 GMT 20 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2006193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- The Free Democratic Party of Germany [FDP] 
rejects the introduction of a "voluntary police reserve" and 
broader use of the Bundeswehr at home. Corresponding proposals 
by the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union 
[CDU/CSU] would water down the current division of tasks, FDP 
Secretary General Hoyer told journalists in Bonn today. It is 
necessary to fill the 30,000 vacant positions among the police 
and not opt for "superficial solutions that might turn out to be 
dangerous." 
  After a meeting of the FDP Presidium, Hoyer stressed that 
the 
Liberals are against a "spare-time police," as suggested by 
Interior Minister Manfred Kanther (CDU). The current division 
of the monopoly of power must be maintained, according to which 
internal threats must be fought by the police and external 
threats by the Bundeswehr. "Internal security is too important. 
Thus, the citizens must not be put off with makeshift 
solutions," Hoyer pointed out. 

</TEXT>

