<H3> <TI>   Industry Minister `Satisfied' With EU Steel Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industry Minister `Satisfied' With EU Steel Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1606143794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1408 GMT 16 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1606143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Gnutti Satisfied With Revised Steel </F>
Plan"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, June 16 -- Industry Minister Vito 
Gnutti on Thursday [16 June] said he was "fairly satisfied" with 
the conditions set by the European Commission for the approval 
of a revised restructuring plan for the steel industry. 
  "We must still define some points," Gnutti said after 
meeting 
the European competition commissioner, Karel Van Miert, adding: 
"There are no particular problems, it's a question of setting 
times" for application of the agreement. 
  The European Commission yesterday came up with a new plan 
allowing the Italian government to give steel companies 415 
million ECUs (493.5 million dollars) to finance production 
cutbacks through plant closings. Gnutti said his talks with Van 
Miert were going very well and that the Rome government may 
approve the plan and set aside the funds at tomorrow's cabinet 
meeting. 
  The plan, which was declared all but dead last month, would 
have Italy to reduce its production by some five to six million 
[metric] tons, allowing the EU [European Union] to near its goal 
of reducing overall capacity production by 19 million tons. 
The plan will have to be approved by EU industry ministers who 
will meet in Brussels next Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

