<H3> <TI>   Industry Minister Unveils Decentralization Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industry Minister Unveils Decentralization Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1506143994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1304 GMT 15 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1506143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Gnutti Unveils Industry Ministry </F>
Decentralisation"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, June 15 -- Industry Minister Vito 
Gnutti today unveiled plans to bring ministerial services closer 
to its users, especially the small and medium firms that are 
Italy's industrial backbone. 
  The essence of the plan is decentralisation, a concept close 
to the heart of a Northern Leaguer like Gnutti. A user-friendly 
network of outlets will be set up nationwide, providing 
businessmen with the information they often complain is slow in 
coming from central offices in Rome, on tax breaks, funding, law 
changes, and work opportunities. 
  For the preparatory period, Gnutti said a six-month 
extension 
would be necessary for staff seconded into the Industry Ministry 
from other departments including the now-defunct southern 
development agency. After that, staff will be taken on to man 
the new outlying offices. 
  Boosting small and medium-sized industry is a key goal of 
the 
new-look ministry, Gnutti told the press. His targets include: 
stepping up relations with the anti-trust authority; enhancing 
protection for the consumer; transferring technology to small 
and medium firms; seeking out new markets; boosting funding to 
smaller firms; fostering broader share ownership; and pressing 
on with ministry re-organisation. 
  On privatisations, Gnutti confirmed the government's 
intention to press ahead with the disposals of INA [National 
Insurance Institute], ENI [National Hydrocarbons Corporation], 
ENEL [National Electric Power Board]. On EFIM [Manufacturing 
Industry Holding and Financial Company], he recalled that the 
liquidation deadline is January 25, and revealed that problems 
in the armaments, rail and aluminium sectors had emerged from 
talks with liquidator Alberto Predieri. 

</TEXT>

