<H3> <TI>   Paris Urges EU, G-7 Aid for Chernobyl Closure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paris Urges EU, G-7 Aid for Chernobyl Closure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1606180294 Paris AFP in English 1704 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1606180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Paris, June 16 (AFP) -- French Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur said Thursday [16 June] France would urge its 
European and G7 partners to provide aid that would enable 
Ukraine to shut down the volatile Chernobyl nuclear plant. 
  He said France would call on its partners to help resolve 
the 
Chernobyl "problem" at the European Union [EU] summit on June 24 
and 25 at Corfu and at next month's meeting of the G7 leading 
industrial nations in Naples. 
  The question of closing Chernobyl -- which Ukraine says it 
cannot afford to do unaided -- is on the agenda for both 
meetings. 
  The plant at Chernobyl -- the site in April 1986 of the 
world's worst civilian nuclear accident -- constituted "a very 
serious danger" on safety grounds, Balladur added. 
  The main priority was to "put an end to the production of 
electricty from the Chernobyl plant," he said. 
  "We must help the Ukranian Government to build three more 
modern and risk-free power plants.... That presupposes helping 
Ukraine, whose economic and financial situation is disastrous," 
he said, adding: "Helping Ukraine is a major priority." 
  Balladur stressed that electricity produced at Chernobyl and 
sold in Central Europe was one of Kiev's few assets. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

