<H3> <TI>   Kohl Meets European Trade Union Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Meets European Trade Union Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006164894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1517 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The preconditions for establishing 
European works councils in the European Union (EU) could be 
created soon. Fritz Verzetnitsch, president of the European 
Trade Unions Confederation (ETUC), was optimistic following 
talks between an ETUC delegation and Chancellor Helmut Kohl in 
Bonn today that a guideline to this effect will be adopted 
during Germany's EU presidency, which starts on 1 July. 
European works councils are the necessary answer to the 
increasing internationalization of decisions made by big 
companies. 
  At the same time, Verzetnitsch made clear that European 
trade 
unions expect the EU to step up initiatives to combat 
unemployment and to expeditiously adopt a European social 
charter. Europe's social unity is limping behind schedule, he 
claimed. 
  Government spokesman Dieter Vogel said that the chancellor 
and the ETUC delegation agreed that combating unemployment is 
the central task of the EU and its member states. European 
integration must be given a fresh impetus. 
  Chancellor Helmut Kohl confirmed that guidelines on the 
establishment of European works councils, on part-time work, and 
on short-term employment contracts are a high priority for the 
German Government. Great importance is attached to the social 
dialogue with trade unions and employers' associations in the 
European unification process. A Europe geared to people's needs 
requires unions and management who help shape social realities 
in the member countries and in the Community, the chancellor 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

