<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government May Grant Exile to Haiti Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government May Grant Exile to Haiti Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006225994 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 2207 GMT 
20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2006225994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Spanish sources in Washington told Radio Nacional 
that the military junta in Haiti could be granted political 
asylum in Spain if the United States were to request it. 
President Bill Clinton has admitted implicitly that one of the 
possible solutions for the current crisis in Haiti -- and its 
return to democracy -- would be that the military leaders who 
took part in the coup d'etat be exiled in Spain or in France. 
Our correspondent in Washington Luz Rodriguez has the story. 
  Spanish sources have confirmed to Radio Nacional de Espana 
that our country would be willing to receive the three Haitian 
military leaders for which the United States is looking for a 
golden exile. 
  The leaders they are talking about are Commander in Chief 
Raoul Cedras; Michel Francois, the head of Port-au-Prince 
police; and Philippe Biamby, the chief of Army general staff. 
  We have not been able to confirm that the United States has 
made a formal request to Madrid because it is still not clear 
whether the three Haitian leaders are willing to go into exile 
even though this exile would be in the best of circumstances. 
The aim of this operation would be to allow the return of Jean 
Bertrand Aristide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

