<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christian Party Leaves Cabinet Over EU Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Christian Party Leaves Cabinet Over EU Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2006132594 Paris AFP in English 1237 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2006132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Helsinki, June 20 (AFP) -- The tiny Christian Party 
in Finland's center-right coalition government, headed by Prime 
Minister Esko Aho, decided on Monday [20 Jun] to leave the 
cabinet after differences of opinion over European Union [EU] 
membership. 
  Toini Kankaanniemi, minister for development aid and the 
party's only representative in cabinet, submitted his 
resignation to the premier after Aho denied him the right to 
vote against the government during a ballot to decide who would 
sign the country's EU membership agreement this weekend in Corfu. 
  The parliamentary group of the Christian Party decided later 
to leave the government and refrain from naming a new minister. 
  All seven members of the party in the 200-member parliament 
oppose Finland's plans to join the EU. 
  Last week the government defeated a no-confidence motion on 
its plans to join the EU next year, with members of the 
Christian Party abstaining. 
  The government, which was set up in April 1991 after general 
elections, also includes Aho's Centre Party (former Agrarian 
Party), the Conservatives and the Swedish Party, representing 
the Swedish-speaking minority in Finland. 
  With the withdrawal of the Christian Party, the government 
has backing from 108 MPs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43741 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu119_n_94003" </HT>


