<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   ANAP's Yilmaz Discusses Aid With Christopher </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ANAP's Yilmaz Discusses Aid With Christopher </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2106104594 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 2055 
GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2106104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report] </F>
  [Text] Motherland Party [ANAP] leader Mesut Yilmaz has 
declared that linking the U.S. military aid to Turkey to issues 
other than security and to certain conditions is unacceptable. 
Yilmaz, who is currently in the United States for the World 
Forum meetings, began his contacts in Washington. TRT 
correspondent Yavuz Yorulmaz reports from Washington: 
  [Begin Yorulmaz recording] Yilmaz first met with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher. In a statement after the 
20-minute meeting, Yilmaz said that bilateral relations and the 
developments in Turkey's region were assessed with Christopher. 
Yilmaz reported that during the meeting he emphasized that it is 
unacceptable to Turkey to link the military aid to conditions. 
Yilmaz said: Relating this subject to matters other than 
security -- such as terrorism, against which Turkey is 
struggling in a very legitimate way; or the Cyprus problem, a 
national issue which Turkey has been following for 20 years -- 
is an unacceptable situation for Turkey. 
  Yilmaz said that Christopher, in turn, remarked that the 
U.S. 
Administration does not find it appropriate to link the military 
aid to Turkey to conditions and that it will intervene with 
Congress on this matter. Yilmaz noted that he also informed the 
U.S. secretary of state that the Turkish public has serious 
concerns regarding Poised Hammer and that this concern is 
related to Iraq's territorial integrity. 
  Pointing out that during the meeting he also briefed 
Christopher on the work conducted in Turkey with regard to 
constitutional amendments, Yilmaz added: I conveyed to 
Christopher that it would be extremely wrong to confuse 
terrorism with the human rights issue, that the Turkish state 
will in no way renounce its legitimate struggle against 
terrorism, but that this struggle should not distract us from 
certain steps we must take in the area of human rights. 
  Yilmaz said that during the meeting, he expressed the view 
that the U.S. Congress decision to impose an embargo on 
Azerbaijan is very unjust and that the U.S. Administration 
should adopt a more balanced attitude with regard to the 
Azerbaijani-Armenian conflict. 
  The ANAP leader later met with some members of the U.S. 
Congress at a luncheon hosted in his honor by Turkish Ambassador 
Nuzhet Kandemir. In a speech at the dinner, Yilmaz stated that 
Turkey's importance increased further in the wake of the Cold 
War and that Turkey is playing a constructive role in its 
region. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

