<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Institute, U.S. Firm To Cooperate on AIDS Cure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Institute, U.S. Firm To Cooperate on AIDS Cure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206084494 Paris AFP in English 1705 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2206084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 21 (AFP) -- The U.S. firm Sheffield 
Medical Technologies and a French government research institute 
announced Tuesday [21 June] they would join forces to develop a 
French-conceived AIDS vaccine. 
  Tests using a prototype of the vaccine on monkeys have been 
promising, said Jean-Claude Chermann, head of the National 
Institute of Health and Medical Research and a co-discoverer of 
the AIDS virus in 1983 when he worked at the Pasteur Institute. 
  If all goes well, tests on humans will begin in mid-1995 
under the supervision of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, 
he added. 
  The vaccine is designed to be taken orally along with the 
polio vaccine, which is relatively low-cost and easy to use, and 
thus make the AIDS vaccine widely accessible in Africa, he added. 

</TEXT>

