<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Rejects Opposition Appeal Against Privatization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Rejects Opposition Appeal Against Privatization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1606142294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 0945 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1606142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 16 (A.A.) -- The Constitutional Court 
on Wednesday [15 June] rejected a demand by a number of deputies 
against the government's law on authorizing privatization. 
  The court rejection took place by a narrow margin of one 
vote 
(six votes rejected the request and five accepted it). 
  The law in question gives broad powers to the government to 
issue decrees in the force of law to privatize state enterprises. 
  Junior coalition partner Social Democratic Populist Party 
(SHP) Deputy Mumtaz Soysal and his 90 colleagues from various 
political parties had applied a while ago to the Constitutional 
Court to abolish the law, asking for the `stoppage of the 
implementation of the law.' 
  Privatization is one of the main objectives of the coalition 
government led by Prime Minister Tansu Ciller and was included 
in the government's economic package on April 5. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

